"Ono T., Shiomoto A., Saino T.","Recent decrease of summer nutrients concentrations and future possible shrinkage of the subarctic North Pacific high-nutrient low-chlorophyll region",2008,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","22","3", GB3027,"","",,,10.1029/2007GB003092,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65549117263&partnerID=40&md5=4910c1b313d8c15cec01aca28ff7e3a3","Subarctic Fisheries Oceanography Division, Hokkaido National Fisheries Research Institute, Kushiro, Japan; Faculty of Bio-industry, Tokyo University of Agriculture, Abashiri, Japan; Hydrospheric Atmospheric Research Center, Nagoya University, Nagoya, Japan; Institute of Observational Research for Global Change, JAMSTEC, Yokosuka, Japan; Subarctic Fisheries Oceanography Division, Hokkaido National Fisheries Research Institute, 116 Katsurakoi, Kushiro 085-0802, Japan; Hydrospheric Atmospheric Research Center, Nagoya Universify, Furo-cho, Chikusa-ku, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan; Faculty of Bio-industry, Tokyo University of Agriculture, 196 Yasaka, Abashiri 099-2493, Japan","Ono, T., Subarctic Fisheries Oceanography Division, Hokkaido National Fisheries Research Institute, Kushiro, Japan, Subarctic Fisheries Oceanography Division, Hokkaido National Fisheries Research Institute, 116 Katsurakoi, Kushiro 085-0802, Japan; Shiomoto, A., Faculty of Bio-industry, Tokyo University of Agriculture, Abashiri, Japan, Faculty of Bio-industry, Tokyo University of Agriculture, 196 Yasaka, Abashiri 099-2493, Japan; Saino, T., Hydrospheric Atmospheric Research Center, Nagoya University, Nagoya, Japan, Institute of Observational Research for Global Change, JAMSTEC, Yokosuka, Japan, Hydrospheric Atmospheric Research Center, Nagoya Universify, Furo-cho, Chikusa-ku, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan","We found evidence that summertime surface nutrient concentration in the subarctic North Pacific (SANP), the third largest ""high-nutrient and low-chlorophyll"" (HNLC) region in the world oceans, has decreased during 1975 to 2005. The observed trend seemed independent from natural decadal/interannual variations and roughly explained by the combination of multidecadal increasing trend of sea surface temperature (SST) and the observed negative correlation of nutrient concentration vs. SST. These analyses indicated that the observed decrease is mainly due to the recent stratification of the upper ocean column caused by global warming. This nutrient trend has a potential to minimize the present SANP-HNLC region by up to 25%, assuming that the observed trend continues until the end of this century. Copyright 2008 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Negative correlations; North Pacific; Nutrient concentrations; Nutrients concentrations; Sea-surface temperatures; Upper oceans; World oceans; Atmospheric temperature; Chlorophyll; Eutrophication; Global warming; Ocean engineering; Oceanography; Porphyrins; Seawater; Submarine geophysics; Nutrients; annual variation; chlorophyll; decadal variation; global warming; nutrient cycling; sea surface temperature; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (North)",,,,,,"Anderson, L.A., Sarmiento, J.L., Redfield ratios of remineralization determined by nutrient data analysis (1994) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 8, pp. 65-80; Aumont, O., Maier-Reimer, E., Blain, S., Monfray, P., An ecosystem model of the global ocean including Fe, Si, P colimitations (2003) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 17 (2), p. 1060. , doi:10.1029/2001GB001745; Chiba, S., Ono, T., Tadokoro, K., Midorikawa, T., Saino, T., Increased stratification and decreased lower trophic productivity in the Oyashio region of the North Pacific - A 30-year retrospective study (2004) J. Oceanogr., 60, pp. 149-162; Conkright, M.E., (2002) World Ocean Atlas 2001: Objective Analysis, Data Statistics, and Figures, CD-ROM Documentation, 17p. , National Oceanographic Data Center, Silver Spring, MD; Doney, S.C., Evaluating global ocean carbon models: The importance of realistic physics (2004) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 18, pp. GB3017. , do